article.description:
Kevin Garnett made sure the Minnesota 
Timberwolves got off to a quick start this time.
article.headline: Garnett and Co. take control from the start
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- The big difference between the Timberwolves and the Knicks was just that: bigness.
Garnett

Kevin Garnett had 25 points, 15 rebounds and seven assists Sunday night as Minnesota outsized and outmuscled the overmatched New York Knicks 106-88. Using their substantial height advantage to control the inside, the Wolves also got 17 points from Joe Smith and 14 from Gary Trent while shooting 57 percent from the field. ''That's every night, no matter what the height differential is, we're trying to pound you inside,'' Trent said. ''Teams that dominate the paint dominate this league. There's very few teams that are winning championships from the perimeter. ''More points in the paint, more rebounds in the paint, more layups -- that usually turns into more wins,'' Trent said. Coming off a 14-point home loss to New Jersey and about to begin a grueling four-game stretch against the Kings (twice), Jazz and Lakers, the Wolves took advantage of the only weak opponent they'll see for a while. Garnett shot 10-for-18, Trent was 6-for-8 and Smith was 6-for-9. Rod Strickland added 13 points and seven assists, the majority of his scoring coming in the fourth quarter when the Knicks went without a point guard in an effort to make a comeback. ''We played pretty bad against New Jersey. They really put a number on us. We had a team meeting this morning and made some adjustments as far as what we need to work on,'' Garnett said. Allan Houston scored 32 points despite being defended by Garnett, but the Knicks trailed by double digits for almost the entire second half in losing for the 10th time in 12 games this season. After Houston hit a 3-pointer to pull the Knicks to 95-86, Shandon Anderson committed consecutive turnovers and Lee Nailon added a third. Strickland and Garnett each scored four points in an 8-0 run as the Knicks struggled just to get a shot off, making it 101-85 with 2:14 left. The Knicks had as many turnovers as field goals (seven) in the final 12 minutes. ''It's hard when you have bad stretches,'' Houston said. ''It's like a virus goes through the whole team. It's a bad habit that we have to break out of.'' The Timberwolves took control early, using a 10-0 run to open a 25-16 lead late in the first quarter. Garnett had eight points and eight rebounds at the end of the first quarter, and 18 points and 11 rebounds by halftime as the Timberwolves led 51-45. Garnett's double-double was his NBA-leading 13th of the season. Trent scored on three consecutive possessions and Garnett had assists on the Wolves' next two trips downcourt as they built a 71-60 lead. New York had a 5-0 run immediately after Garnett sat for a rest, leading coach Flip Sanders to yell at the team during a timeout. Smith then came out and made a three-point play, and Minnesota carried an 80-69 lead into the fourth quarter. ''Their big guys were dominant,'' Latrell Sprewell said. ''You have me at (small forward) guarding Trent or KG, it makes it very difficult. Me guarding KG is a huge mismatch.'' Game notes
Knicks G Charlie Ward missed his sixth consecutive game with a bruised leg. His status remains day-to-day. ... Sprewell, Houston and Howard Eisley each had four turnovers. Garnett and Strickland each had three steals. ... The Knicks have until Dec. 2 to use a $4.5 million injury exception in a trade, and coach Don Chaney said there were no centers or ''impact players'' being offered to New York, only power forwards. ''We already have an overload of power forwards. Just once I'd like to see a 7-footer who can play,'' Chaney said. ''When teams are looking at us, they're thinking we're eager to make a deal. But nobody's knocking our doors down right now.''
